| Blizzard Seeks to Block User Rights, Privacy                       |
|   from the still-haven't-downed-netherspite dept.                  |
|   posted by CmdrTaco on Tuesday April 10, @08:33 (Privacy)         |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/10/124218           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "In the overlooked case between [0]Blizzard
and [1]MDY Industries, the creator of the WoWGlider bot, Blizzard is
arguing that using any programs in conjunction with the World of Warcraft
constitutes copyright violation. Apparently [2]accessing the copy of the
game client in RAM using another program infringes upon their rights.
Under that logic, users do not even have the right to use anti-virus
software in the event that the game becomes infected. Furthermore,
Blizzard's legal filings downplay the role of their [3]Warden software,
which actively scans users' RAM, CPU, and storage devices (and
potentially sensitive data) and sends information back to Blizzard to be
processed."

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/10/124218

