| Google Pushes Open Source OCR                                      |
|   from the google-has-taken-all-knowledge-to-be-its-provice dept.  |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday April 10, @14:02 (Google)              |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/10/171244               |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]SocialWorm writes "Google [1]has just announced work on [2]OCRopus,
which it says it hopes will 'advance the state of the art in optical
character recognition and related technologies.' OCRopus will be
available under the Apache 2.0 License. Obviously, there may be search
and image search implications from OCRopus. 'The goal of the project is
to advance the state of the art in optical character recognition and
related technologies, and to deliver a high quality OCR system suitable
for document conversions, electronic libraries, vision impaired users,
historical document analysis, and general desktop use. In addition, we
are structuring the system in such a way that it will be easy to reuse by
other researchers in the field.'"

